06272nam a22009495i 9783110672237DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106722377 a10.1515/97831106722372doi  a(DE-B1597)534963  a(OCoLC)1135585748  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBL820.B2bD96 2020 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a398.20938/0122300aDionysus and Rome :bReligion and Literature /ced. by Fiachra Mac Góráin. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ;v9300tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tList of illustrations -- tList of Contributors -- tIntroduction. Dionysus in Rome: accommodation and resistance -- tThe ancient reception of Euripides’ Bacchae from Athens to Byzantium -- tImages of Dionysus in Rome: the archaic and Augustan periods -- tLiber, Fufluns, and the others: rethinking Dionysus in Italy between the fifth and the third centuries BCE -- tDionysian associations and the Bacchanalian affair -- tDionysus/Bacchus/Liber in Cicero -- tBacchus and the exiled Ovid (Tristia 5.3) -- tAlius furor. Statius’ Thebaid and the metamorphoses of Bacchus -- tThe shadow of Bacchus: Liber and Dionysus in Christian Latin literature (2nd–4th centuries) -- tIndex rerum et nominum -- tIndex locorum -- tIndex of inscriptions and visual artefacts0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile most work on Dionysus is based on Greek sources, this collection of essays examines the god’s Roman and Italian manifestations.Nine contributions address Bacchus’ appearance at the crossroads of Greek and Roman cultures, tracing continuities and differences between literary and archaeological sources for the god. The essays offer coverage of Dionysus in Roman art, Italian epigraphy; Latin poetry including epic, drama and elegy; and prose, including historiography, rhetorical and Christian discourse.The introduction offers an overview of the presence of Dionysus in Italy from the archaic to the imperial periods, identifying the main scholarly trends, with treatment of key Dionysian episodes in Roman history and literature. Individual chapters address the reception of Euripides’ Bacchae across Greek and Roman literature from Athens to Byzantium; Dionysus in Roman art of the archaic and Augustan periods; the god’s relationship with Fufluns and Liber in the 4th and 3rd centuries BCE; Dionysian associations; Bacchus in Cicero; Ovid’s Tristia 5.3; Bacchus in the writings of Christian Latin writers.The collection sheds light on a relatively understudied aspect of Dionysus, and will stimulate further research in this area.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aBacchus. 4aDionysos. 4aRom. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aBacchus.  aDionysus.  aRome.1 aMac Góráin, Fiachra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMac Góráin, Fiachra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aManuwald, Gesine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMassa, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiano, Daniele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, John F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerris, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchiesaro, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteinhauer, Julietta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWyler, Stéphanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel